<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-1')">1</a>. &quot;Crypto-&quot; is used to designate a secret adherence to a faith, usually in response to persecution and forced conversion.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-2"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-2')">2</a>. The Czech people have been historically characterized as tolerant and even indifferent towards religion for hundreds of years. This remains true today, with 86.7% of the Czech Republic describing themselves as non-religious or undeclared.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-3"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-3')">3</a>. The Ahnenerbe Obskurakorps was a Nazi organization tasked with the study and the containment/destruction/creation of anomalies. As a sub-group of the SS, the organization answered directly to Heinrich Himmler. The organization was composed of scientists, field operatives, and occultists (most of which were former members of the Thule Society).</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-4"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-4')">4</a>. From Proto-Uralic *ńä(x)li + *-ka, meaning &quot;hunger&quot;. As noted in my previous case study, &quot;Sarkic&quot; is a pejorative term used by the Greek speaking Mekhanites, considered by many to be the predecessors of the modern Church of the Broken God.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-5"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-5')">5</a>. A hagiography (from Greek ἅγιος, hagios, meaning 'holy', and -γραφία, -graphia, meaning 'writing') is a biography of a saint or an ecclesiastical leader.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-6"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-6')">6</a>. Resurrection includes what many would refer to as &quot;necromancy&quot;. Sarkites do not appear to distinguish between the two the way Abrahamic traditions do.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-7"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-7')">7</a>. <em>Németh</em> has been shown to function in a way remarkably similar to class B amnestics. The substance is usually self-applied much the way one would apply cologne or perfume, leaving the Divoši unaffected for reasons unknown. Their ability to tolerate the solution may help explain their unnaturally strong resistance to Foundation amnestics.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-8"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-8')">8</a>. Klavigar Nadox was one of Ion's four disciples and is associated with intelligence, wisdom, perception, and mysteries. Epithets include: the Tongueless Speaker, Lord of Mysteries, the All-Seeing, and the Anticipation of Ion.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-9"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-9')">9</a>. &quot;Luxury&quot; is generally interpreted as spices and other flavor enhancing ingredients. Most only follow the latter part of the law during the high holidays. Meat that has been cured is generally considered acceptable as well.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-10"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-10')">10</a>. Depressants such as alcohol and opium are forbidden, as they inhibit or dull the senses, while the use of stimulants is tolerated. The use of hallucinogenics is highly encouraged and plays an important part in religious ceremonies.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-11"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-11')">11</a>. Jaka translates as &quot;divide&quot;, &quot;separate&quot;, or even &quot;cull&quot;. It is employed in Sarkicism as a concept of cosmic justice, separating the strong from the weak, the good from the evil, adherent from apostate - terminating those deemed enemy or unnecessary. To Sarkites, vengeance and justice share a single form.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-12"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-12')">12</a>. Sarkic scripture, roughly translated as &quot;book&quot; or &quot;scroll&quot;.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-13"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-13')">13</a>. Straight edge is a subculture of hardcore punk whose adherents refrain from using alcohol, tobacco and other recreational drugs, in reaction to the excesses of punk subculture. This can also extend to refraining from promiscuous sex, following a vegetarian or vegan diet or not using caffeine or prescription drugs.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-14"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-14')">14</a>. Another term for Grand Karcist Ion, though the true meaning of the word appears to be lost.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-15"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-15')">15</a>. Klavigar Lovataar was one of Ion's four disciples and is associated with sex, love, eroticism, pleasure, motherhood, disease, and unrestrained reproduction (breeding, cancers, growth, etc.). Epithets include: the One Whom Ion Most Desired, the Highblood Redeemer, and the Mother (on rare occasion &quot;Brood&quot; or &quot;Hive&quot; Mother).</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-16"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-16')">16</a>. Klavigar Saarn was one of Ion's four disciples and is associated with darkness, secrecy, deception, poison, assassination, and justice. Epithets include: the Whisperer, the Coiled Shadow, the Faceless One, and the Judgment of Ion.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-17"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-17')">17</a>. &quot;And I later wondered, had it been crafted from the bones of various creatures, or had it come directly from some Sarkic created chimera?&quot;</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-18"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-18')">18</a>. Psi-resistant humanoid containment cells have spherical interiors and are composed of a lead-aluminium alloy between two stainless steel frames. These containment cells are equipped with Psi-inhibitors alternating between 32 and 66 kilohertz.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-19"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-19')">19</a>. A reference to the Sarkic practice of &quot;shepherding the flesh&quot;. Serves as another term for fleshshapers.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-20"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-20')">20</a>. Based on the year and location of the subject's birth, this &quot;Charles&quot; was most likely a reference to Charlemagne.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-21"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-21')">21</a>. An Irminsul (Old Saxon, likely meaning &quot;great/mighty pillar&quot; or &quot;arising pillar&quot;) was a sacred pillar-like object attested as playing an important role in the Germanic paganism of the Saxon people. The oldest reference to an Irminsul describes it as a tree trunk erected in the open air. The purpose of the Irminsuls remains unknown.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-22"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-22')">22</a>. John Dee (13 July 1527 – 1608 or 1609) was an English mathematician, astronomer, astrologer, occult philosopher, and advisor to Queen Elizabeth I. He devoted much of his life to the study of alchemy, divination, and Hermetic philosophy.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-23"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-23')">23</a>. Sir Edward Kelley (1 August 1555 – 1 November 1597), was an English Renaissance occultist and self-declared spirit medium. He is best known for working with John Dee in his magical investigations.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-24"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-24')">24</a>. Most likely the subject's faithful followers.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-25"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-25')">25</a>. Judah Loew ben Bezalel (1512 – 1609) widely known to scholars of Judaism as the Maharal of Prague, or simply The Maharal, the Hebrew acronym of &quot;Moreinu Ha-Rav Loew&quot; (&quot;Our Teacher, Rabbi Loew&quot;), was an important Talmudic scholar, Jewish mystic, and philosopher who served as a leading rabbi in the cities of Mikulov in Moravia and Prague in Bohemia. Due to his unprecedented impact on Jewish study, he is considered one of the most important rabbis of all times. He is also the subject of a legend that he created the Golem of Prague, an animate mythological being fashioned from clay.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-26"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-26')">26</a>. A puzzle box, as the name implies, is a container that can only be opened by solving one or more puzzles.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-27"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-27')">27</a>. In the case of this particular puzzle box, deterrents included the ejection of barbed projectiles soaked in tetrodotoxin and an anomalously effective flesh-eating virus capable of converting a human body to slurry in less than 10 minutes.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-28"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-28')">28</a>. The Divoši mourn their dead through excarnation (defleshing) and cannibalization. The bones are then anointed with oil, to render the Spirit invisible to the Archons.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-29"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-29')">29</a>. Or &quot;Of Nature's defiance&quot;, another possible translation. This resembles the Ouroboros, an ancient symbol depicting a serpent or dragon eating its own tail, which the Sarkites associate with the process of apotheosis - the transformation of mortal into deity.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-30"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-30')">30</a>. Likely a reference to the &quot;flight or fight&quot; response.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-31"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-31')">31</a>. The Worm of Midnight is a constellation in Sarkic astronomy, believed to coincide with the constellation Eridanus. Of possible interest to the Foundation, this is also where the CMB cold spot is located, sometimes hypothesized as the Eridanus Supervoid or Great Void. Cosmic voids are vast spaces between filaments (the largest-scale structures in the universe), which contain very few or no galaxies.</div>
